> **CLAUDE DIRECTIVE**: ALWAYS use SAFE_TO_STRING macros for console output to prevent crashes.

## 1. Console Output Standards
Follow these for safe printing.

@console_rules [
  {
    "id": "safe_string",
    "rule": "Always wrap variables in SAFE_TO_STRING before outputting.",
    "severity": "high"
  },
  {
    "id": "avoid_std_to_string",
    "rule": "Use SAFE_TO_STRING instead of std::to_string().",
    "severity": "high"
  },
  {
    "id": "initialize_console",
    "rule": "Initialize the console at program start.",
    "severity": "high"
  },
  {
    "id": "use_safe_macros",
    "rule": "Use SAFE_* macros for brevity.",
    "severity": "medium"
  }
]

## 2. Best Practices and Enforcement

- Prevent crashes from invalid conversions
- Enforce via static analysis (clang-tidy custom checks)
- Auto-fix in code generation when possible

## 3. Example Usage

```cpp
// ❌ WRONG - Direct std::to_string can crash
std::cout << "Value: " << std::to_string(value) << std::endl;

// ✅ CORRECT - Use SAFE_TO_STRING
std::cout << "Value: " << SAFE_TO_STRING(value) << std::endl;

// ✅ CORRECT - Short form macros
SAFE_INT(42)
SAFE_FLOAT(3.14f)
SAFE_DOUBLE(2.718)
```

